  <static seed="1295" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/complexFractions30.pg">
    <statement><p>Calculate the following. Use an improper fraction in your answer.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{3}{ \frac{6}{5} - \frac{2}{5} } =}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{15}{4}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simplify a complex fraction, we find the common denominator of all fractions. In this case, it is <m>5</m>. We multiply the complex fraction<rsq/>s numerator and denominator by this common denominator, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{3}{ \frac{6}{5} - \frac{2}{5} } 
      \amp = \frac{3 \cdot 5}{ (\frac{6}{5}-\frac{2}{5}) \cdot 5 } \\
      \amp = \frac{15}{ \frac{6}{5} \cdot 5 - \frac{2}{5} \cdot 5 } \\
      \amp = \frac{15}{ 6  - 2 } \\
      
      \amp = {{\frac{15}{4}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Here is a simple way to do fraction multiplication:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \frac{6}{5} \cdot 5 = 5 \div 5 \cdot 6 = 6 }</m></p>
</solution>
